import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import statsmodels.api as sm
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    plt.scatter(data['engineers'], data['population'])
    plt.xlabel('Percentage of Engineers')
    plt.ylabel('Population')
    
    if len(plt.xticks()[0]) > 20:
        plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MaxNLocator(20))
    
    plt.title('What is the correlation between the percentage of engineers and the population in each state?', wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
chart.show()
```

```python
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    data = data.sort_values(by='engineers', ascending=False)
    ax = data.plot.bar(x='state', y='engineers', legend=False)
    ax.set_ylabel('Percentage of Engineers')
    ax.set_xlabel('State')
    
    if len(plt.xticks()[0]) > 20:
        ax.xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MaxNLocator(20))
    
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.title('Which state has the highest percentage of engineers?', wrap=True)
    
    max_engineers_state = data.iloc[0]['state']
    max_engineers_value = data.iloc[0]['engineers']
    ax.axhline(max_engineers_value, color='r', linestyle='--', label=f'{max_engineers_state}: {max_engineers_value:.2f}')
    ax.legend()
    
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
```

    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
